<TEXT>
the justice department is considering freezing 
assets of savings and loans and sampl officers accused of fraud but 
most of the cases already under investigation wont be affected 
the authority to freeze the funds was included in last years 
sampl bailout bill passed by congress justice spokesman david runkel 
said tuesday it became effective on aug 10 
because the bill is not retroactive however the fraud or other 
wrongdoing must have been committed after that date for assets to 
be frozen runkel said 
thus far no appropriate cases have been found since most 
of the cases being scrutinized by the dallas bank fraud task force 
concern allegations of wrongdoing that go back several years 
the spokesman said 
nevertheless he said a large number of cases remain under 
investigation 
i cant tell you that this is going to lead to substantial 
sums being attached but its a possibility runkel said and 
its something were looking at exploring for possible use 
the freezing of assets would be done before a final court 
judgment is entered on criminal or civil cases and would prevent 
assets from being dissipated as the legal process is carried out 
he said 
we would have them so that they would be available for 
recapture by the government after a verdict he said 
the announcement came about a month after a house subcommittee 
chairman said thousands of sampl fraud investigations were not being 
actively pursued for lack of money 
the sampl legislation enacted in august authorized 75 million for 
pursuing bank and thrift embezzlement this year but the 
administration sought and received only 492 million in actual 
appropriations from congress said rep doug barnard dga 
he said 2327 cases of financial institution fraud and 
embezzlement were inactive meaning they were open but not being 
pursued of those 1298 are considered major cases involving 
losses of 100000 or more barnard told his house government 
operations subcommittee on commerce consumer and monetary affairs 
justice spokesman doug tillett said at the time we are 
putting every penny to work on the problem 
the slew of texas sampl cases and the vast amount of money lost 
prompted the justice department to turn to the new method of 
gaining funds 
throughout the sampl scandal the government has found that the 
assets have disappeared before they can be retrieved runkel said 
out of the dallas bank task force weve had 125 million in 
recovery and the alleged illegal activities and the cost to 
the taxpayers has been substantially more than that in the 
hundreds of millions of dollars out of the dallas cases alone 
runkel said 
what happens is that the assets are not there following a 
conviction he said 
the dallas task force has brought charges against 62 people of 
whom 49 have been convicted the justice department said criminal 
fines against the 49 total 574850 and restitution orders total 
119 million 
attorney general dick thornburgh met tuesday with timothy ryan 
who was sworn in monday as the director of the treasury 
departments office of thrift supervision 
representatives of the two will meet later this week to 
develop specific plans to ensure the most efficient use of the 
resources provided by congress runkel said 
the day before the announcement the administration acknowledged 
that its 50 billion savings and loan bailout will not be enough a 
congressional report has said costs could reach 500 billion if the 
economy falters that estimate includes the governments borrowing 
expenses over 40 years 
</TEXT>
