<TEXT>
antiindian taunts and posters greeted 
supporters of tribal treaty rights tuesday night at a lake where a 
band of chippewas prepared to open the tribal spearfishing season 
an estimated 350 supporters and opponents of chippewa 
spearfishing gathered at cedar lake in northwestern wisconsin amid 
tight security 
more than 100 law enforcement officials including more than two 
dozen in riot gear were at a boat landing at the lake the lake 
was the only one the st croix chippewas had said they would fish 
many other northern lakes remain covered by ice 
when members of the american indian movement arrived beating a 
drum in support of chippewa spearfishing the crowd swelled around 
them and taunts were exchanged 
red black and white spearing aint right some said 
save the walleye spear the indian one man shouted 
posters held by those in the crowd had such messages as you 
have shamed every native american that ever lived equal 
rights not treaty rights and walleye or welfare make a 
choice 
kevin wakefield of star prairie said he came to the boat landing 
for the first time because indian spearfishing must stop 
they are spearing the walleye out of the lakes it is just 
take take take wakefield said 
some aim members photograped the crowd which adults and 
children 
it was not clear however if there had been any fishing polk 
county sheriff ben ware said he understood one boat of spearers 
went out but state spokesman jeff welch said he understood there 
had been no spearfishing 
the st croix band one of six chippewa bands in wisconsin has 
been authorized to take 2102 walleye from offreservation lakes 
over the course of the spearfishing season that usually lasts three 
weeks said tribal chairman ed bearheart 
before going to the lake about 100 spearfishing supporters 
signed a pledge of peace and donned armbands said barb kass of 
luck coordinator for the treaty support group witnesses for 
nonviolence 
about 25 representatives of the minneapolisbased aim including 
founder clyde bellecourt attended a rally at the st croix bands 
community center before heading to the lake 
since 1983 federal courts have upheld 19th century treaties 
giving the chippewa the right to hunt fish and harvest timber on 
offreservation lands in the northern third of wisconsin 
tensions between chippewa spearers and nonindian critics have 
grown each year since 1985 when the indians renewed active 
spearfishing a year ago 271 spearers caught 16000 walleye 
demonstrations last year opposing indian spearfishing mostly 
near the lac du flambeau reservation escalated into incidents 
involving rockthrowing and racial slurs more than 200 people were 
arrested 
state and tribal leaders have urged supporters and opponents of 
indian spearfishing to stay away from boat landings this spring 
