<TEXT>
facing the prospect of losing their 
104yearold dairy farm albert and carol kobbermann became so 
battered emotionally that they considered seeking counseling 
but they didnt take the 30mile trip from their farmstead to 
the clinic in willmar because they feared their neighbors prying 
eyes 
when youre hit pointblank with a problem its what other 
people think that you worry about not whats best for yourself 
carol kobbermann said as she recalled her familys feelings during 
the farm crisis five years agoits difficult to admit that 
things are out of control you feel like a failure 
the stigma of seeking help is one of several difficulties in 
rural mental health care that are to be the subjectd at a public 
hearing thursday in marshall in southwest minnesota its the 
first of four hearings planned this year by the national advisory 
mental health council and the national mental health leadership 
forum 
the biggest problem that we face in rural areas is first a 
culture that says there arent emotional problems in our part of 
the country and second of all if there are we dont admit it 
said rep vin weber rminn who will speak at the hearing 
the extreme financial stress brought a lot of those problems 
out into the open then we had to say hey we really have 
problems with teenage suicide spousal abuse depression and other 
mental and emotional disorders he said p vincent mehmel 
executive director of the west central community services center in 
willmar said the center is busiest during the hard financial times 
farmers who have lost their crop or who have suffered a 
significant loss depression is there mehmel said were also 
subject to the problem of unstable families we once thought 
divorce and child and spouse abuse was an urban problem now its 
a rural problem too 
statistics show the effect of hard times on mental health in the 
sixcounty area with 120000 residents that mehmels center 
serves 
medical assistance reimbursements for mental health care made to 
meeker county residents in 1986 at the peak of the farm crisis 
had increased 907 percent over the figure reported two years 
earlier the figures increased 669 percent in swift county and 
454 percent in chippewa county 
mehmel also deals with the difficulties of recruiting 
psychologists to rural settings where the money prestige and 
cultural amenities dont match those of metropolitan areas 
its hard to get them and when you do get them they move on 
in a few years he said to get a stable staff is a very 
difficult thing 
about 5500 patients visit the centers 30 mental health 
professionals annually no one knows how many are afraid to seek 
help 
the major problem is the mindset that its not ok to get help 
for mental problems said marlyn benson the centers rural 
outreach coordinator youre supposed to be tough and strong 
pull yourself up by your bootstraps dont cry and ask for help 
its easier in a metro area to get help and not have your 
