<TEXT>
a landmark biotechnology case is in the hands 
of californias supreme court which will decide whether a leukemia 
patient can sue for a share of the profits from an anticancer drug 
derived from his cells 
the high court heard arguments tuesday in the case of john 
moore who claims blood cells from his cancerous spleen were 
wrongfully used by the university of california two ucla 
researchers and two drug and biotechnology companies that helped 
develop the drug 
university attorney allen wagner and lawyers for other 
defendants argued that the development of lifesaving drugs will be 
seriously impeded if the justices rule that moore has property 
rights to tissue and cells removed from his body 
they said that would require researchers to negotiate and pay 
for human tissue used for research and drug development 
a decision in moores favor would have a devastating impact on 
medical research said peter abrahams lawyer for defendant 
shirley quan a research assistant at ucla 
moore the 45yearold president of a seattle soft drink 
company said he is merely trying to defend the rights of the 
individual patient in the case where the physicianresearcher is 
also a businessmanentrepreneur 
without my knowledge or consent the doctors and the research 
institutions used a part of me for their own gain moore said 
outside court they stole something from me 
the high courts ruling is expected within 90 days a ruling in 
moores favor would allow his 1984 lawsuit to go to trial the case 
was dismissed by a los angeles superior court in 1986 then 
reinstated in 1988 by a 21 vote of a state appeals court 
during tuesdays 70minute hearing the seven justices asked 
questions that suggested sympathy with moores claim but indicated 
a reluctance to extend personal property rights to cells taken from 
an organ after it is surgically removed 
moore was an alaska pipeline surveyor in 1976 when he sought 
treatment for hairy cell leukemia at ucla dr david golde removed 
moores spleen the standard treatment for the rare leukemia and 
his disease went into remission 
after the spleen was removed golde discovered it contained 
unique blood cells that produced a blood protein called gmcsf now 
in experimental use as a drug to stimulate the immune system to 
fight certain cancers and possibly aids 
moores attorney sanford gage said moore never was told his 
cells had great potential value yet for nearly seven years golde 
and others brought moore from seattle to los angeles for blood and 
other tests while they developed moores cells into a 
selfperpetuating cell line to massproduce gmcsf 
in 1984 ucla received a patent for the cell line naming golde 
and quan as the inventors 
the same year moore sued university of california regents 
golde quan genetics institute inc of cambridge mass and 
sandoz pharmaceuticals corp of east hanover nj 
the lawsuit claimed the defendants wrongfully converted to 
their own use moores personal property namely blood cells from 
his spleen he also alleged they failed to obtain his informed 
consent and breached their fiduciary responsibility to him 
goldes attorney anthony murray argued that moores diseased 
spleen was worthless and golde and other defendants gave 
commercial value to the blood cells through their own efforts 
its not as if you tap a tree and take maple syrup out of it 
put the maple syrup in a bottle and sell it murray said 
diseased tissue has no commercial value 
gage replied that moores cells were vital to creating the cell 
line and the drug 
moore is seeking only that share of drug proceeds that can be 
separated from the efforts of the researchers and manufacturers of 
the drug gage has argued that the market for lymphokines a family 
of drugs that includes gmcsf has been estimated at as much as 3 
billion 
he said deals that led to gmcsfs development and production 
resulted in golde and others getting genetics institute stock now 
worth 3 million ucla and golde also received research grants 
worth 440000 from genetics institute and sandoz gage added 
the doctors were interested in commercial exploitation yet 
they did not reveal that to him justice stanley mosk said 
wasnt there an element of deception 
but justice david eagleson said that if moores claim is upheld 
any patient treated with drugs derived from his cells might be 
accused of illegally converting moores property 
</TEXT>
