jurek a solidarity parliament deputy 
at least one solidarity deputy aleksander malachowski said 
mazowiecki would be a better candidate for president 
the discussion of a presidential bid by walesa comes just days 
before the solidarity labor union is due to hold its first national 
congress in nine years 
walesa has said he is committed to winning reelection as 
solidarity chairman at next weeks congress but he is expected to 
face a challenge from union members who feel solidarity has strayed 
from its original ideals of 1980 by putting politics ahead of 
tradeunion goals such as defending workers interests 
walesa has also found himself in conflict with the mazowiecki 
government which he has accused of acting too slowly in 
privatizing the statedominated economy and removing other remnants 
of the old communist system 
in general solidarity members of parliament and the government 
have been content to move more slowly toward new voting for 
parliament and the presidency 
the main argument for delaying new elections is that for the 
present a nationwide campaign would be too divisive and distract 
energies from the fundamental task of restructuring the economy and 
local governments 
local government elections are scheduled for may 27 and the next 
parliamentary vote is not due until 1993 
those close to walesa have argued for holding elections more 
quickly because of public impatience for political change during a 
time of great economic sacrifice 
