<TEXT>
the captain of the scandinavian star 
today testified at a maritime inquiry into last weekends ferry 
disaster that he had been awakened by a crewman who told him 
someone is playing arsonist 
capt hugo larsen also rejected allegations by passengers that 
safety was substandard and that his crew of filipino and portuguese 
sailors was unprepared for an emergency 
police in sweden said they have recovered the bodies of 127 
people but up to 200 people may have died when flames engulfed the 
10500ton ship on a voyage from norway to denmark in one of the 
worst recorded fires at sea 
on tuesday a maritime commission from three scandinavian 
countries agreed to crack down on foreignflagged ships and tighten 
safety regulations for all passenger ferries 
larsen said he went to sleep at midnight but was roused by an 
officer at 155 am saturday reporting that woolen blankets were 
burning in a passageway on the port side of the ship 
someone is playing arsonist larsen quoted the officer as 
saying 
shortly afterward another crew member reported smoke in the 
ship and fire patrols discovered fires on both sides of the ship 
almost simultaneously larsen told the inquiry 
the fire spread incredibly fast at the midships section he 
said 
the captain said he had checked safety and fire fighting systems 
and the crew underwent a boat drill before the ships first 
scandinavian voyage on april 1 a fire drill had been planned for 
sunday the day after the fire destroyed the ship he said 
he also rejected charges from passengers who told reporters the 
crewmen could not communicate with them he said most spoke 
usable english and responded well in the crisis 
the inquiry headed by maritime and trade court president frank 
poulsen was expected to hear 15 or 20 witnesses norwegian police 
were heading a separate investigation 
in oslo norwegian police withdrew a decision to release the 
names of 186 people believed dead or missing from the fire on the 
voyage to the danish port frederikshavn 
the list was intended to help clear up the mystery of how many 
people were on board the 20yearold ferry when it caught fire 
but deputy police chief arne huuse said families objected that 
it would appear more like a death list than a list of missing 
required for the investigation 
latest estimates put the number of passengers and crew at 530 
but the figure has changed constantly as bodies were recovered and 
the fate of rescued passengers clarified there were instances 
where people were listed twice said oeystein berger of the oslo 
police 
in the swedish port of lysekil investigators said the work of 
recovering bodies from the firegutted ship was slowing as it 
became harder to collect the remains 
they are mostly ashes sometimes there are two three or four 
people together said police spokesman leif skoglund 
the ferry was towed to lysekil still smoldering on saturday 
evening it took until sunday night to extinguish the fire which 
burned at temperatures reaching 570 degrees consuming everything 
combustible in the midships sections 
at a meeting late tuesday the maritime directors of sweden 
norway and denmark approved tighter measures to inspect ships 
flying foreign flags of convenience in nordic waters 
about 60 million passengers travel nordic routes every year 
more than three times the total populations of the three countries 
twelve ships including the nassauregistered scandinavian star 
fly foreign flags 
the commission decided that the foreignflagged ships should 
undergo safety checks by a nordic maritime authority said a 
statement released by the danish maritime board 
until now primary responsibility for safety standards has been 
with the registering country and foreignflagged ships were 
subjected to spot checks 
the statement said crews must demonstrate fire fighting 
qualifications and training for emergency evacuations the group 
also decided to require complete passenger lists on ferries 
traveling at night it said 
