april 8 
roswell nm daily record on immigration reform and 
discrimination 
comprehensive immigration reform was designed to curtail illegal 
immigration it is not a license to discriminate against 
mexicanamericans or legal aliens or americans who look or sound 
foreign 
apparently however discrimination has been the unintended 
result according to a recent report by the general accounting 
office the immigration reform and control act has indeed produced 
a widespread pattern of discrimination some are having trouble 
finding work because employers fear the consequences of the law 
congress now must respond under the 1986 law a finding of 
widespread discrimination requires lawmakers to reconsider 
employer sanctions within the next 30 days repealing sanctions is 
an option although less extreme options are available and at 
this point preferable 
illegal immigration continues to be a problem particularly 
along the usmexico border area immigration reform was a 
goodfaith effort to respond now that effort needs to be 
calibrated the law cannot be an excuse to discriminate 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
april 6 
the greenwood miss commonwealth on mississippi delta problems 
the final report of the mississippi delta development commission 
is due next month the findings of the commission are being awaited 
with interest 
congress allocated 3 million to study economic conditions in 
impoverished regions of seven states bordering the mississippi 
river mississippi louisiana arkansas tennessee kentucky 
missouri and illinois the study is to be concluded with a 10year 
plan for economic development 
even as the report is being finalized preliminary information 
is circulating among those recently submitting data were 
sociologists forrest a deseran and joachim singlemann of louisiana 
state university their principal conclusion was that the delta 
region stands apart from the mainstream and if it is to 
become competitive in the national economy it needs help now 
to facilitate their study the researchers divided the 214county 
area into 27 labor markets they found that the top third of the 
labor markets compared favorably to national averages unemployment 
rates and poverty evident in the bottom twothirds however show 
the extent of the task at hand 
in those 18 labor markets the average unemployment rate is 36 
percent higher than the national average their per capita income 
is less than 75 percent of the us total and their families are 
more than twice as likely to be poor as the average american 
</TEXT>
