april 7 
shawano wis evening leader on college basketball 
march madness lived up to its name this season with the college 
basketball tournament more competitive than it has ever been but 
while the game itself couldnt be healthier there are still many 
problems with a sport that puts such a high price on winning 
college presidents talk of running clean programs with an 
emphasis on players who graduate then they turn around and fire 
coaches who do both of those things why because their teams dont 
win more often 
the system that is still being used amounts to nothing more than 
a tremendous incentive to cheat currently each of the 64 schools 
selected for the ncaa tournament receives upwards of 250000 with 
each ensuing tournament victory worth an additional 250000 
schools that advance to the final four are raking in over 1 
million 
unless the system is changed those numbers are only going to 
increase next year when the ncaa enters into a sevenyear 1 
billion tv contract with cbs in effect tripling the money from the 
last contract 
the tournaments growing popularity has nothing to do with the 
money involved it would be followed just as closely if the players 
were playing strictly for a championship trophy and not some 
milliondollar check for their school besides there is something 
inherently wrong about unpaid amateur athletes earning enormous 
sums of money for an institution 
by simply distributing the 1 billion among all 291 division i 
schools and eliminating the huge financial rewards given to winning 
teams some of the pressures on coaches and athletes would be 
removed 
