<DOCNO> AP900411-0076 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
american businesses plan to increase spending 
on plant and equipment by a healthy 76 percent this year the 
government said today in a report reflecting renewed optimism about 
the economy 
the commerce department said a survey completed in march found 
businesses planning to spend 5034 billion for expansion and 
modernization this year 
if realized that would surpass the previous record of 4678 
billion in capital spending set last year 
this year would mark the fourth consecutive increase in 
investment however the rate of growth would be the slowest in 
three years capital spending rose 86 percent in 1989 89 percent 
in 1988 and 42 percent in 1987 
the new estimate for capital spending growth in 1990 is only 
slightly below last years rise and represents a substantial 
increase from an earlier survey of 1990 plans released in december 
at that time businesses said they planned to boost spending by 
only 49 percent 
all of the figures have been adjusted for inflation 
the earlier survey occurred when many economists were predicting 
a recession this year since then the economy has proved more 
resilient than expected and as a consequence companies have planned 
for expansion more optimistically 
the projected increase in spending would be good news for the 
economy providing needed momentum this year at a time when the 
stimulus from a shrinking trade deficit is fading 
economists say the increased productivity that results from 
investment spending is the only way in the long run to bolster 
economic growth the federal reserve board has been keeping 
interest rates relatively high in an attempt to keep the economy 
from overheating and fueling inflation 
the 76 percent investment increase for all industries includes 
a 46 percent rise in manufacturing and a 95 percent increase for 
companies engaged in mining transportation and other 
nonmanufacturing areas 
manufacturing and housing have been the sectors of the economy 
hardest hit by the feds tight money policy 
manufacturers are projecting investment spending this year of 
1902 billion the anticipated rate of increase although lower 
than the average for all industries was still sharply up from the 
14 percent projection in december 
the manufacturing gain includes a 22 percent rise in durable 
goods and a 66 percent increase for nondurables durable goods 
are big ticket items expected to last three or more years 
everything from washing machines to warships because buyers 
usually borrow to buy durable goods their sales are more sharply 
depressed by high interest rates 
in the december survey durable goods manufacturers had 
projected a 15 percent drop in investment spending 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

