<TEXT>
an atlase rocket 
roared toward space today carrying three small scientific 
satellites on a 22 million mission aimed at improving military 
communications and aiding navigation 
the 96foot rocket lifted off the pad at space launch complex3 
at 8 am said maj tom worsdale an air force spokesman at this 
sprawling coastal military base 140 miles northwest of los angeles 
it looked excellent he said its the smoothest launch 
ive seen in the year ive been here everything went perfect 
worsdale said the rocket flew south over the pacific ocean and 
the satellites weighing from 120 to 150 pounds each went into 
orbit at 815 am 
the three satellites containing four experiments were 
propelled toward a 460mile polar orbit by the atlas which was 
topped by a scoutaltair upper stage booster 
the mission was named p872 stacksat the air force hasnt 
explained the meaning of p872 but stacksat means the satellites 
were stacked atop the rocket for launch 
the atlas similar to the one that lifted john glenn to the 
first manned orbit of earth in 1962 was built by general dynamics 
and once served as a nuclear warheadtipped intercontinental 
ballistic missile at forbes air force base in kansas it was 
refurbished in 1987 for use in launching payloads into space 
the instruments on the three research satellites will help make 
navigation charts and test ways to overcome phenomena in earths 
atmosphere that can interfere with military and other 
communications 
the devices will be turned on in about 30 days and operate for 
at least a year capt mark goodman project manager said in a 
statement issued before the launch 
the uppermost satellite named polar orbiting geomagnetic 
survey contains two experiments the first is a magnetometer that 
will measure the strength of the earths magnetic field at various 
locations the data will be used to help construct new defense 
mapping agency geomagnetic charts which are updated every five 
years as the magnetic field changes 
the satellite also contains the solid state recorder experiment 
meant to demonstrate the use of highspeed integrated circuit 
designs as computer memory devices in space said ed parsons chief 
spokesman for the air forces space systems division in los angeles 
the second satellite named tex or transceiver experiment will 
study communications problems by bouncing radio waves off the 
ionosphere the part of earths atmosphere rich with electrically 
charged particles 
the third satellite the selective communications experiment 
carries a variablepower radio transmitter that will also bounce 
radio waves of varying frequencies off the ionosphere for similar 
studies 
</TEXT>
