<TEXT>
the nations businesses shrugging off 
economists gloomy recession predictions have significantly 
increased their plans for modernization and expansion this year 
the government said wednesday 
the commerce department said a survey completed in march found 
businesses planning a record 5034 billion in plant and equipment 
spending in 1990 up 76 percent from last year 
businesses had projected a much less optimistic 49 percent rise 
in an earlier survey released in december when many analysts were 
forecasting the imminent end of the economys sevenyear expansion 
the significance of this is its one more piece of evidence 
were not going into a recession said economist gordon richards 
of the national association of manufacturers capital spending 
will be providing some strength to an otherwise weak 
economy 
if the new projections are realized spending would surpass the 
previous record of 4678 billion set last year and would mark the 
fourth consecutive increase capital spending rose 86 percent in 
1989 89 percent in 1988 and 42 percent in 1987 
all the figures have been adjusted for inflation 
the surprisingly strong investment plans come at a time of 
generally sluggish economic growth and declining corporate profits 
most analysts are forecasting growth as measured by the gross 
national product of around 2 percent this year down from 3 
percent last year 
the survey indicates businesses appear to be looking beyond the 
slowdown and are making the improvements they need to ensure 
increased productivity and better profits in the future economists 
said 
despite all the stories of gloom and doom you read this 
shows that businesses are not as shortsighted as many say 
said economist stephen s roach of morgan stanley amp co 
over time capital spending not only will bolster economic 
growth it will increase profits and ease inflation he said 
the current profit squeeze is being caused by companies 
inability to pass on higher costs to their customers modernization 
spending should help eliminate the production bottlenecks that are 
driving up those costs he said 
the report should be received as good news at the federal 
reserve which has been using relatively high interest rates to 
dampen economic growth and prevent demand from swapping production 
capacity and adding to inflation pressures 
the feds wish list is probably not so much an economic 
slowdown but a shift from consumer spending to savings and 
investment roach said 
economist bruce steinberg of merrill lynch said capital spending 
plans are weakest in businesses most affected by lackluster 
domestic demand for big ticket durable goods such as autos 
and strongest in sectors supported by strong overseas demand such 
as paper aircraft and nonelectrical machinery 
the 76 percent planned investment increase for all industries 
includes a 46 percent rise in manufacturing and a 95 percent 
increase for companies engaged in mining transportation and other 
nonmanufacturing areas 
manufacturers are projecting investment spending this year of 
1902 billion the anticipated rate of increase although lower 
than the average for all industries was still sharply up from the 
14 percent projection in december 
the manufacturing gain includes a 22 percent rise in durable 
goods and a 66 percent increase for nondurables durable goods 
are items expected to last three or more years everything from 
washing machines to warships because buyers usually borrow to 
purchase durable goods those sales are more easily depressed by 
high interest rates 
in the december survey durablegoods manufacturers had 
projected a 15 percent drop in investment spending 
before adjusting for inflation the department predicted a 78 
percent increase for all businesses this year to 5128 billion 
after rising 104 percent last year that was up from the earlier 
1990 forecast of 64 percent 
