<TEXT>
an international antidrug summit of 112 nations 
rejected the idea of legalizing narcotics and instead called 
wednesday for a wide range of actions to cut both supply and demand 
of drugs 
earlier in the final day of the threeday conference doctors 
warned that the spread of aids by drug users was increasing 
worldwide 
while strongly rejecting legalization the delegates disagreed 
on punishment for drug abusers however they did back alternatives 
to prison for offenders who want treatment 
us delegates said users must be held accountable but 
authorities from the netherlands said drug abusers should be 
treated like alcoholics or smokers 
delegates were also at odds over programs to make sterile 
needles available to drug users to reduce the spread of aids 
through contaminated needles 
us secretary of health dr louis w sullivan questioned 
research findings showing such programs did not promote increased 
drug use he said the us government refused to fund such programs 
the 35point declaration adopted at the end of the drug 
conference sponsored by britain and the united nations noted that 
the drug market was no longer confined to industrial nations but 
had spread to developing countries 
the declaration called for action at the community neighborhood 
and family level as well as the national and international level 
to prevent drug abuse it said drug education should be started in 
elementary school 
the declaration committed delegates to giving higher priority to 
fighting drugs on all fronts reducing demand eliminating crops 
and drug trafficking preventing laundering of drug money and 
promoting effective treatment and rehabilitation 
us and british experts told a final committee meeting 
wednesday that increased drug use in the developing world was 
raising the number of drug abusers infected by hiv the virus that 
causes aids 
where three years ago hiv infection among drug injectors was 
seen as a developed world problem it is now really seen as a 
worldwide problem said dr don c des jarlais of beth israel 
hospital in new york 
developing countries particularly thailand argentina and 
brazil all reported hiv infection rates among drug injectors of 40 
percent or more in the last three years des jarlais said 
and there is concern that other places where drug injection is 
common such as the middle east are subject to rapid epidemics of 
the spread of hiv among drug users he said 
dr david hawkins of st stephens clinic and westminster 
hospital in london said that by the end of 1990 there are 
projected to be more aids cases in injecting drug users than in 
homosexual men in europe 
aids or acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a deadly 
affliction in which a virus attacks the bodys immune system it is 
spread mainly by sexual contact the use of contaminated needles 
among drug abusers and transfusion of tainted blood 
