<DOCNO> AP900411-0108 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a 29yearold atlas 
rocket that once was armed with nuclear warheads thundered into 
space wednesday carrying three small research satellites into a 
polar orbit 
it took off quickly and was gone in an instant said air 
force spokesman maj tom worsdale everyone was pleased with the 
smoothness of the operation and the success of the launch 
the 91foottall atlase topped by a 5foottall scoutaltair 
upper stage booster blasted off the pad at space launch complex 3 
at 8 am pdt emerging from a low fog bank over this sprawling 
coastal military base 140 miles northwest of los angeles 
the liquidfueled atlas similar to the rocket that lifted john 
glenn to orbit earth in 1962 flew south over the pacific fifteen 
minutes after liftoff the solid fuel upper stage separated from 
the payload delivering the three satellites into a polar orbit 460 
miles above earth worsdale said 
the mission cost 22 million said ed parsons chief spokesman 
for the air forces space systems division in los angeles 
one satellite will test new computer memory circuits and measure 
earths magnetic field to help make navigation charts used by ships 
and planes 
the others will test a new communications device and study 
phenomena in earths upper atmosphere that interfere with 
spacetoground radio communications said capt mark goodman 
project manager 
the atlas was built in 1961 by general dynamics and once served 
as a nuclear warheadtipped intercontinental ballistic missile at 
forbes air force base in kansas it was refurbished in 1987 for use 
as a launch vehicle 
the air force originally planned to launch the three satellites 
on a scout rocket but none was available atlase rockets normally 
launch larger payloads such as weather satellites the atlas 
launched wednesday had what the air force described only as 
slightly degraded performance that prevented it from lofting a 
heavier payload 
each satellite weighs only 120 to 150 pounds 
the uppermost satellite named polar orbiting geomagnetic 
survey contains a magnetometer to measure the strength of the 
earths magnetic field at various locations 
the data will be used to help draw new defense mapping agency 
geomagnetic charts many ships and aircraft navigate using 
computerized versions of the charts which are updated every five 
years as the magnetic field changes goodman said 
the satellite also contains the solid state recorder experiment 
meant to demonstrate the use of highspeed integrated circuit 
designs as computer memory devices in space and to make sure they 
can withstand the radiation in space parsons said 
the second satellite named tex or transceiver experiment will 
bounce radio signals of different power levels off the ionosphere 
the part of earths upper atmosphere containing irregularities that 
can disrupt highfrequency radio communications 
the third satellite the selective communications experiment 
will conduct similar studies by bouncing radio signals of varying 
frequencies off the ionosphere the air force hopes to learn what 
power and frequency levels can be used to overcome disruption of 
radio communications 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

