<TEXT>
for the fifth month in a row americans paid 
more attention to foreign news than domestic news in march the 
times mirror center for the people and the press reported wednesday 
in its monthly survey of reader interest the news industry 
organization listed 18 news stories ranging from lithuanias 
declaration of independence to the ncaa basketball playoffs 
it asked people which was the most important 
forty percent of those responding cited an international story 
with 21 percent naming lithuanian independence also mentioned were 
other political developments in the soviet union east germany and 
elsewhere in eastern and central europe two percent named the 
release of black leader nelson mandela from a south african prison 
four percent mentioned domestic stories including oil spills 
the basketball playoffs the death of 87 people in a fire at a 
social club in new york and the attempt in idaho to pass a bill 
that would severely restrict abortions 
ten percent named stories not on the list as the most important 
43 percent said they didnt know and 2 percent refused to answer 
this adds up to only 99 percent because the percentages were 
rounded to the nearest full number 
the organization also asked questions about president bush and 
said 74 percent of those responding replied that they approved of 
the way he is handling his duties sixteen percent disapproved the 
rest refused to answer or said they didnt know 
sixtyfour percent said they were optimistic that bush would 
make progress in solving the countrys longterm problems 
in response to more specific questions 46 percent said he was 
doing an only fair job in dealing with longterm economic 
problems 42 percent that he was doing only fair on long term 
health care problems 43 percent that he was doing only fair on 
longterm education problems and 39 percent only fair on longterm 
environmental problems 
the percentages rating his performance good or poor were 
smaller only 2 to 5 percent of those responding rated him 
excellent in dealing with the various issues 
people were also asked what vegetable it is that bush recently 
said he wouldnt eat seventysix percent answered correctly that 
it was broccoli four percent named some other vegetable and 20 
percent didnt know or wouldnt answer 
the survey results are based on telephone interviews conducted 
under the direction of princeton survey research associates april 
58 the survey covered 1212 adults aged 18 or older the gallup 
organization did the interviewing the results are subject to a 
sampling error of 3 percentage points 
the times mirror center for the people and the press is an arm 
of times mirror a corporation that owns the los angeles times and 
other publishing and broadcasting enterprises 
