<TEXT>
the army will no longer shoot goats to train 
physicians at fort sam houston to treat gunshot wounds a 
physicians group that sought the moratorium said wednesday 
the physicians committee for responsible medicine said 800 to 
1000 goats were being shot each year at the san antonio texas 
base 
the practice continues at fort bragg nc and as many as 1200 
goats are involved the committee said 
dr neal d barnard a psychiatrist and president of the 
organization said the group sought in moratorium after specialists 
such as radiologists and psychiatrists who normally dont treat 
trauma victims were told to participate in the fort sam houston 
training 
its not a very nice thing to be shooting these animals 
secondly its not even very good training barnard said 
the wound of a goat is far different from a human wound he 
said shooting a goat in the leg has no relation to an abdominal 
wound or a chest wound or a head wound the tissue feels 
different in the goat its got thick hairy skin 
barnard said the army had been shooting goats to train doctors 
since 1958 
pat davis chief of public affairs for the armys academy of 
health sciences at fort sam houston said she couldnt confirm how 
long the shootings had been taking place the ban took effect about 
90 days ago 
the physicians group she said was inaccurate in saying the 
goats were being shot the army uses a firing mechanism which 
she described as a small square box to fire a projectile or 
metal pellet into a goats leg 
the military had been using the pellets to simulate the 
shocking impact of firing at a human from a military weapon 
military weapons fire projectiles at a far higher speed than 
handguns she said 
military weapons cause a great deal of destruction to the 
tissue she said if military physicians dont clean the wound 
correctly the guy will lose his limb and probably his life 
barnard said the armys decision was only temporary and that his 
organization would push for a permanent ban along with a ban at 
fort bragg 
ms davis said she was not sure whether the ban was permanent or 
temporary goats will still be used for other surgical procedures 
she said 
</TEXT>
