<TEXT>
a report that called the oyster creek 
nuclear generating station the nations worst plant for protecting 
workers from radiation has come under heavy criticism from the 
employees themselves 
my friends make a lot of jokes about me glowing in the dark 
said margaret martin a radiological control worker who has worked 
at the plant since 1988 thats just lack of education 
a study released tuesday by public citizen a washingtonbased 
organization founded by consumer advocate ralph nader said there 
were 2875 incidents of worker exposure at oyster creek in 1988 
the figure is double the plants 1987 exposure mark and triple 
the 1988 average of the nations other 106 commercial nuclear power 
plants according to the report glowing on the job 
gleaned from nuclear regulatory commission documents the report 
also said oyster creek the nations oldest commercial plant still 
in operation had the secondhighest number incidents of worker 
exposure from 1980 to 1988 among 20 plants considered the nations 
worst oyster creeks 20486 cases of worker exposure trailed only 
the 27701 recorded at pilgrim 1 in plymouth mass 
at the end of work tuesday many of oyster creeks 990 workers 
said they were aware of the risks of working at a nuclear plant 
but do not believe they are in any greater danger than their 
counterparts nationwide 
they brainwash you to make it sound like its dangerous 
said jeff manning who has worked at oyster creek for three months 
this place doesnt bother me a bit said roger mengle a 
waretown man who has handled hazardous materials at the plant since 
june before that he worked for eight years at three mile island 
in middletown pa which was the site of the nations worst 
commerical nuclear accident 
this is my job mengle said 
some oyster creek workers said they chose to work in the nuclear 
industry because of the high pay 
theres better money to be made here said martin 
oyster creek spokesman sandy polon said he would not divulge the 
range of salaries at the plant 
karl neddenien another plant spokesman said the report was 
needlessly alarming 
neddenien did not dispute findings that each worker was exposed 
to an average dose of radiation equivalent to 26 chest xrays but 
argued that nonplant workers in ocean county receive naturally 
occurring background radiation that is more than 40 percent of that 
figure 
neddenien said that although oyster creek which began producing 
electricity in 1969 had more exposures than the nations other 
commerical nuclear plants the level was well within federal 
standards for total exposure 
neddenien also said the stations older design required more 
employees to work in a more compact area exposing them more 
frequently 
working in a nuclear power plant entails possible exposure to 
radiation neddenien said its certainly not a surprise 
he said officials are trying to reduce the number of worker 
exposures by installing permanent scaffolding inside the plants 
dry well to prevent workers from spending extra time setting it up 
before repairs he also said more radiation shielding is being 
installed 
harry sharma of toms river a nuclear engineer for nine years 
said the exposure to radiation was relative 
if you fly on a plane you get radiation it doesnt mean you 
dont fly were still within the limits and the limits are 
artifically low he said 
oyster creek is a subsidiary of general public utilities corp 
of parsippany it is operated by gpu nuclear corp and owned by 
jersey central power amp light which gets power from oyster creek 
for about 200000 of its 800000 customers 
</TEXT>
