a federal judge on wednesday gave former 
national security adviser john poindexter convicted of five felony 
counts in the irancontra scandal an extra week to file motions 
for a new trial 
us district judge harold greene approved the extension until 
april 24 sought tuesday by the office of poindexters attorney 
richard w beckler 
the office of independent counsel lawrence e walsh which has 
been investigating the irancontra scandal since december 1986 
filed court papers wednesday saying it did not oppose the extension 
becklers motion requested the extra time to file motions for a 
directed verdict of acquittal and for a new trial both of which 
would require the judge to set aside last saturdays jury verdict 
frederick robinson an attorney with becklers office who signed 
the request for the extra time said the motions will not be based 
on new evidence but he declined to say what arguments will be made 
those are things were working out now he said im not 
at liberty to get into all the grounds yet 
the deadline for such motions without an extension would have 
been april 17 he said 
poindexter 53 was convicted saturday of conspiracy 
obstruction and lying to congress he could face up to 25 years in 
prison and 125 million in fines when he is sentenced june 11 
beckler said immediately after the conviction that he planned to 
appeal 
were naturally disappointed with the verdict in this case 
but were going to appeal it and were going to keep fighting it as 
hard as we can beckler said at the time 
poindexter was the third top reagan administration figure 
convicted in the scandal the others former poindexter aide oliver 
north and former national security adviser robert mcfarlane have 
not served any jail time 
poindexter was convicted of conspiring with north businessman 
richard secord and others to conceal the truth about the 
irancontra affair from congress 
specifically poindexter was accused of covering up norths 
secret contra resupply network and the us role in a ciaassisted 
shipment of hawk missiles to iran in november 1985 
norths contra military assistance operation occurred during a 
congressional ban that required the cia to withdraw military 
support for the rebels fighting the sandinista government in 
nicaragua 
