unusually high 
the residue levels on a sample of 10 potatoes among about 300 
tested from 26 fields reportedly were nine times the levels allowed 
by the environmental protection agency all 10 potatoes were from a 
single field 
the epa commended the company for voluntarily halting sale of 
the chemical for use on potatoes 
consumers should not be alarmed and they should continue their 
normal consumption of potatoes said the epa adding that the 
advice was endorsed by the food and drug administration and the 
agriculture department 
aldicarb a toxic chemical that causes flulike symptoms 
including nausea headaches and dizziness is used on a broad range 
of fruits and vegetables to control insects mites and nematodes 
the chemical has been under review at the epa for some time for 
its affect on groundwater and agency officials are considering 
whether to examine possible concerns about residues on food 
products 
while we believe the continued use of aldicarb is safe we 
have a responsibility to the public to conduct additional research 
to determine the reasons for the unexplained residue levels 
rhonepoulenc said in a statement 
aldicarb has been used since 1970 on such crops as potatoes 
