<TEXT>
kentuckys governor signed a bill wednesday making unprecedented 
changes in the administration of his states struggling schools 
and mississippis governor approved nearly 1 billion in aid to the 
nations lowestrated school system 
in frankfort ky gov wallace wilkinson said the bill which 
turns the state into a national laboratory for school reform was 
as significant as drafting the state constitution 
the 1000page statute establishes a minimum spending level of 
2900 for each of kentuckys 570000 students under the old 
system spending varied from 1800 to 4200 a year per student 
depending on a districts wealth 
in the new system geography is a subject to be taught not a 
factor that determines the quality of a childs education said 
wilkinson who said he had been a victim of unequal educational 
opportunity as a child 
the measure raises taxes by about 13 billion over the next two 
years about half the money goes to school reform 
it also eliminates grades for the youngest students and calls 
for committees of parents teachers and principals to make 
daytoday decisions on running schools 
in jackson miss gov roy mabus signed a bill committing 182 
million to improve public school curricula over the next three 
years and another calling for nearly 800 million in bonds to 
replace aging school buildings and buses he called the package 
farreaching and visionary 
but mabus said hed call a special legislative session june 18 
because lawmakers didnt fund the program during their regular 
session which ended friday all of us had a mandate from the 
people to significantly improve the way we educate our children 
he said 
kentuckys law was spurred by a state supreme court ruling last 
june that the states public school system was inequitable and 
unconstitutional and followed nearly a year of political 
wrangling the state has the lowest percentage of high school 
graduates in the nation 
wilkinson signed the bill at the frankfort civic center as 
hundreds of schoolchildren shipped in for the occasion looked on 
the governor said other states face the same sort of court 
orders to restructure their school systems once they see what we 
have accomplished they are sure to follow he said 
in recent years courts have ordered 11 states including 
kentucky to overhaul inequitable school finance systems the 
others are new jersey kansas wisconsin california connecticut 
washington west virginia wyoming arkansas and montana 
in mississippi students have consistently scored lowest in the 
nation on standardized achievement tests although their 
performance has improved since a series of school reforms adopted 
in 1982 
in addition to curriculum improvements the new reform package 
provides for programs to fight illiteracy teenage pregnancy and 
dropouts in the 505000student public school system 
the immediate challenge is finding the money to pay for the 
program mabus proposed a lottery to fund about a third of the 
reform package introduced in august but the senate killed the 
lottery and attempts to revive it mabus rejected the idea of a tax 
increase 
its going to be a difficult task but i think the legislature 
is committed to funding the programs state sen irb benjamin 
who heads the senate education committee said wednesday 
the package calls for the state to finance all curriculum 
improvements and issue bonds to pay for new buildings and buses 
local districts would repay 80 percent of the money borrowed for 
construction projects and 20 percent of the funds for improving 
transportation 
