leaking hydrogen gas fueled a fire and explosion 
that shut down an oilfired generator at the troubled turkey point 
power plant complex wednesday utility officials said no one was 
injured 
two nuclear power plants and another oilfired plant at turkey 
point were not affected spokesmen said the fire was confined to 
an enclosure housing an exciter a small auxiliary generator 
plant operators took the unit 2 generator off line when they 
detected a loss of hydrogen pressure and the fire was discovered 
in the exciter about 15 minutes later said florida power amp light 
co spokesman gary mehalik 
the hydrogen is used to cool the generator 
the visible damage is very very moderate said fpl 
spokesman dale thomas 
the plants fire brigade had to put out the fire twice because 
the highly flammable hydrogen continued leaking and exploded a 
second time he said 
it has an invisible flame but it is searing hot said joe 
jenkins director of the state public service commissions electric 
and gas division 
the hydrogen leaked from the sealed room where the gas cools the 
spinning generator passed through a turbine shaft and into the 
shedsized exciter enclosure mehalik said 
utility workers will have to remove the generator housing on 
unit 2 to determine the extent of damage and the cost of repairs 
and that will take a day or two thomas said 
unit 2 was the only one operating at turkey point at the time of 
the fire which left the 2090megawatt plant idle idefinitely 
one nuclear unit and one oilfired unit were down for scheduled 
maintenance and the other nuclear unit automatically shut down 
monday when an electrical relay failed in an unrelated incident 
the loss of turkey points generating capacity was not 
considered crucial because fpl could boost the power generated at 
other plants or turn on idle units elsewhere in its system 
fpl declared an unusual event at the nuclear plant wednesday 
for almost two hours even though the fire did not affect the 
nuclear side of the operation mehalik said the nuclear regulatory 
commission designation is the lowest emergency classification 
the plants nuclear units have been derided by consumer groups 
as among the most unsafe nationally with a history of security 
lapses and poor training 
the utility responded by launching a major qualitycontrol 
improvement program and won japans most prestigious quality award 
last october the nrc took the plant off its watch list earlier 
this year 
miamibased fpl is floridas largest utility serving 3 million 
