<TEXT>
interior minister salem massadeh said 
wednesday the government next month plans to scrap the 55yearold 
defense law under which martial law has been imposed in jordan 
since 1967 
he said the government will propose a new law for potential 
states of emergency when parliament resumes its sessions early next 
month 
the law will cancel the old law but it will be inactive until 
it is used in emergency cases for the national security of the 
country massadeh told a news conference 
the announcement came as king hussein discussed middle east 
issues wednesday with a senior delegation of us senators led by 
robert dole rkan the senators spent more than three hours with 
hussein after arriving from egypt there were no substantive 
details on the talks 
prime minister mudar badran promised in december to cancel both 
the defense law and martial law within six months 
jordan declared martial law under the 1935 legislation during 
the arabs 1967 war with israel and the country has lived under 
that decree ever since 
but badran this year stripped military courts of most functions 
and returned power to civilian tribunals he declared martial law 
frozen 
both jordan and israel inherited versions of the defense law 
from the british mandate period before world war ii both have used 
it widely 
it provides much of the legal foundation for israels detention 
without trial of thousands of palestinians during the continuing 
uprising on the occupied west bank and gaza strip 
massadeh noted that the many laws and decrees imposed under 
martial law over 23 years often affected routine affairs and he 
said the government is studying which need to be replaced by new 
legislation proposed to parliament 
the action continues a yearlong series of liberalizing reforms 
prompted largely by the april 1989 riots in southern jordan over 
economic problems and what was viewed as government highhandedness 
the parliament that will consider the new legislation was 
elected in november during jordans first nationwide election since 
1967 
jordan has also returned passports confiscated by the general 
intelligence department dropped all travel and work bans and freed 
all of its purely political prisoners according to government 
officials 
massadeh said 31 people convicted of political offenses remain 
in prison but he said all were also convicted of other crimes 
such as possession use or smuggling of arms and explosives or 
attacking security forces 
the us senators meanwhile arranged to fly on to baghdad 
thursday to discuss issues that have strained us relations with 
the iraqi government of president saddam hussein 
