when the telephone company comes calling will 
american creditcard users change their charging ways 
thats the question of the moment in the world of personal 
finance thanks to american telephone amp telegraph cos 
introduction of a combination telephone and credit card known as 
the atampt universal card 
the giantsized venture seems to be off to a promising start 
while the company wont give specifics it has described consumers 
early response to the card as far above initial expectations 
by some outsiders estimates atampt could sign up as many as 5 
million universal cardholders by the end of the year 
but close observers of the financialservices business say the 
ventures ultimate success is by no means assured 
they say it is a lot to expect that large numbers of people who 
get universal cards will cut up and throw away the ones they 
already carry from banks and issuers like american express and 
sears roebuck amp co 
whatever happens analysts add consumers evidently will 
continue to be faced with an old problem paying much higher 
interest rates for creditcard borrowing than they do for just 
about any other type of loan 
this will not shake up the credit card industry says robert 
heady a north palm beach fla publisher of several newsletters 
on banking subjects 
what lured atampt into such a highstakes gamble is plain to see 
the business fed by americans seemingly insatiable passion for 
plastic is big and getting bigger all the time 
in spite of deterrents like taxlaw changes that are eliminating 
deductions for consumer interest more than 20 percent of all 
retail sales in this country excluding automobiles now are paid for 
by credit card up from 116 percent in 1983 
atampt is offering several lures to try to establish a strong 
beachhead in this market for one thing it says customers can 
avoid ever having to pay an annual fee if they apply in 1990 and 
keep using their cards at least once a year 
for another the company is offering 10 percent discounts from 
its prevailing chargecard rates when the card is used for 
longdistance calls 
cardusers who carry a balance from one month to the next will 
pay a variable annual interest rate that is starting off at 189 
percent atampt says 
the rate doesnt differ drastically from industry norms in the 
18 percent20 percent range at a time when rates on mortgages 
home equity loans and auto loans generally run in the 95 
percent125 percent range 
so however much atampt is going to step up the competition it 
evidently has no plans for a price war 
at the same time analysts say the chance to avoid annual fees 
may be attractive to consumers who pay full balances each month 
before interest charges kick in 
but as heady points out atampt is hardly the first issuer to 
offer a nofee card some banks across the country have similar 
deals he observes with lower interest rates to boot 
in sum most analysts believe the addition of a major new 
player doesnt seem likely to change the game very much 
credit cards are essentially perceived as a convenience 
heady says consumers have been paying atrociously high 
creditcard interest rates for years 
