<TEXT>
south americans facing high 
foreign debts ruinous inflation and stagnant economies are 
rejecting radicalism for moderate leaders they hope can solve the 
problems and consolidate democratic rule 
when fernando collor de mello and patricio aylwin became the 
presidents of brazil and chile in march it was the first time all 
12 south american republics were governed by popularly elected 
civilians 
in the past south americans have swung from strident 
proleftists to rightwing military dictators now they are 
abandoning the radical rhetoric and promises of radicals and 
turning to leaders who favor painful steps toward economic order 
history reveals that stable and effective democracies are 
those that present centrist options to the electorate wrote 
manuel dornellas editor and columnist of expreso a conservative 
daily in lima peru 
there is concern that if freemarket economics and democratic 
freedoms do not produce rapid improvements the result may be a 
political tug of war between left and right 
south americans have tried the dictators and the oldstyle 
conservatives said david fleischer a brazilian political 
scientist if this third group of freemarket liberals goes down 
the drain people will vote for the radical left in five years 
which may well prompt a backlash from the military 
fear of such an outcome already has translated into amnesty for 
past violations 
uruguay and argentina have pardoned military officers charged 
with human rights abuses brazil gave amnesty to leftist opponents 
of a 19641985 military regime but did not consider prosecuting 
military chiefs accused of torture 
leftist rebels have been released from jail and secret police 
agencies abolished 
polls in argentina indicate president carlos menem remains by 
far the most popular political figure despite severe austerity 
measures strikes and dissent within his own party 
luis lacalle the new president of uruguay implemented 
austerity demanded by the international monetary fund worked out 
an agreement with the secondlargest party and survived two general 
strikes by the biggest labor federation 
in brazil surveys indicate collors harsh economic plan is 
supported by 80 percent of the people studies done in peru say the 
people are ready for a freemarket economic shock to end rampant 
inflation 
freemarket policies are gaining ground across the continent 
government coddling of domestic businesses promoted by military 
rulers concerned with national security is giving way as argentina 
and brazil strive to create a south american common market 
economic liberalism also has been fostered by concern that the 
foreign aid funds of the united states and other countries are 
being diverted increasingly to eastern europe 
latin american and carribbean countries will receive 350 
million in us aid this year down from 545 million in 1989 
record inflation has given south american leaders the political 
leverage to take bold economic measures here is a brief 
countrybycountry review 
brazil although collor narrowly defeated socialist luis 
inacio da silva in decembers runoff he has mustered public and 
congressional support for a severe plan that includes an 18month 
freeze on 80 percent of bank and investment savings sharp tax and 
utility increases and cuts in subsidies and tax incentives 
argentina menem shocked his laborbacked peronist party by 
raising utility and other rates by several hundred percent 
removing wage price and foreign exchange controls forcibly 
converting bank deposits into government bonds slashing the 
budget and moving to sell moneylosing state companies 
bolivia former president victor paz estenssoro brought 24000 
percent annual inflation down to 16 percent in 1989 by freeing 
prices and the exchange rate closing moneylosing government tin 
mines and reducing a bloated bureacracy jaime paz zamora a 
socialist who succeeded him has announced plans to attract foreign 
capital and sell state industries 
chile aylwin says he will not discard the freemarket 
structure set up by his predecessor gen augusto pinochet who 
kept inflation down to 20 percent a year and built a strong economy 
peru five years of economic chaos under leftist president 
alan garcia bankrupted the country and pushed inflation to 2775 
percent in 1989 novelist mario vargas llosa head of a 
conservative coalition and centrist alberto fujimori are in a 
runoff election to succeed garcia 
venezuela president carlos andres perez outwardly leftist 
when in office a decade ago recently announced imflike economic 
reforms designed to restructure the foreign debt and steer the 
country on a freemarket path 
guyana and suriname mounting foreign debt sharp declines in 
economic output and rising unemployment are forcing socialist 
leaders to alter their policies prime minister hamilton green of 
guyana has said private enterprise doesnt conflict with 
socialism his party seeks foreign capital and imposed unpopular 
fiscal measures demanded by the imf 
ecuador president rodrigo borja a centerleftist favors 
government fixing of exchange and interest rates but has welcomed 
foreign investment kept the state out of major industries and 
declared himself an opponent of inefficient staterun 
enterprises 
how long south americas poor will accept austerity remains a 
question 
riots last year cost 300 lives in venezuela where subsidies 
have been a part of life for 30 years recent protests of increased 
utility and gasoline prices on college campuses led to a violent 
crackdown 
observers in brazil say collor will have about six months to 
stop inflation now running at 4850 percent annually similar 
rumblings are being felt in colombia and guyana 
if solutions dont come from within the system people might 
look for solutions outside the system said federico storani a 
leading argentine congressman who represents the opposition radical 
civic union 
many experts feel moderate leaders will weather the storm 
because of a growing public perception that freemarket policies 
are the only cure for chronic stagnation and inflation 
menem told reporters recently the changes in eastern europe 
are telling us something ideologies in the world have ended the 
world wants to live in freedom wants to be master of its own 
destiny 
