<TEXT>
the unsecured creditors of eastern airlines have 
asked a bankruptcy court to appoint a special trustee to take over 
the ailing carrier and seek a buyer for it 
tuesdays request by the committee of unsecured credits came one 
day after preferred shareholders challenged easterns 
reorganization proposal and submitted a plan that would put the 
airline in the hands of the shareholders unsecured creditors and 
new managers 
the two groups are easterns biggest creditors owed a total of 
more than 16 billion after long supporting management the 
creditors have become exasperated by easterns growing losses and 
its recent plans to cut debt payments 
meanwhile tuesday easterns pilots union won a key victory when 
a federal judge reversed earlier decisions by us bankruptcy judge 
burton r lifland 
us district judge robert w sweet ruled that the union can 
seek arbitration over its contention that eastern has been merged 
with its sister carrier continental airlines 
sweet also decided that the pilots union may proceed with a 
lawsuit against eastern over its practice of leasing aircraft and 
crews from continental 
lifland had previously ruled in both cases that the bankruptcy 
court was the only proper forum for deciding those issues 
in his 71page opinion sweet wrote that the important question 
was when and in what forum collectively bargainedfor rights may 
be enforced against an employer who has sought protection from 
creditors in bankruptcy 
if a court concludes that eastern and continental have 
effectively been merged it would trigger certain protective labor 
provisions such as seniority rights contained in the pilots 
unions contract with eastern 
easterns pilots machinists and flight attendants struck the 
miamibased airline on march 4 1989 forcing it into chapter 11 
bankruptcy protection five days later 
the machinists union remains on strike against eastern 
lifland had denied the pilots request to lift an automatic stay 
protecting eastern against arbitration on the unions contention 
that the transfer of eastern assets to texas air and continental 
constituted a merger between eastern and its sister carrier 
lifland ruled last september that arbitration would usurp the 
bankruptcy courts role in easterns reorganization and thwart 
the goal of judicial speed and economy necessary for 
rehabilitating the airline 
in sweets second ruling the pilots union was allowed to 
proceed with its suit in us district court in miami aimed at 
blocking easterns practice of leasing jets with crews known as 
wetleasing from continental the union had claimed the 
leases violated its contract with eastern because continental 
pilots have been used rather than eastern fliers 
last fall lifland issued an injunction against the unions 
suit maintaining it was an attempt to interfere with the 
bankruptcy courts jurisdiction 
a bankruptcy court hearing on the trustee issue was scheduled 
for friday morning at the same time lifland was slated to 
consider easterns request for 80 million to be withdrawn from 
escrow funds for operating expenses in the second quarter and some 
payments to creditors 
easterns unions have been attempting for some time to have a 
trustee appointed to replace frank lorenzo chairman of easterns 
parent texas air corp the unions accuse lorenzo of funneling 
assets from eastern to continental and to texas air 
