<TEXT>
a deepsea search will be conducted for the 
cargo door that blew off a united airlines jet even though 
investigators determined why nine people were sucked out of the 
airliner over the pacific ocean officials say 
the national transportation safety board voted 30 tuesday to 
blame united the boeing co and the federal aviation 
administration for failure to correct problems with the door of the 
jumbo jet before the feb 24 1989 incident aboard flight 811 
an aviation lawyer meanwhile said the boards conclusions 
should spur the faa into acting more quickly to correct dangerous 
deficiencies in airliners 
ntsb investigators said inspection of the door that popped off 
at 22000 feet carrying a section of fuselage and nine people with 
it still could provide evidence for improving aircraft safety 
a sophisticated navy probe unit will be lowered into the ocean 
in june said board accident investigator ron schleed if it can 
spot the door another device will be dispatched to recover it he 
said 
if they dont find it within 12 to 15 days thatll be the end 
of it schleed said 
the board concluded that even without the door it had enough 
evidence to determine the probable cause of the incident the 
sudden opening of the improperly latched forward lower lobe cargo 
door in flight and the subsequent explosive decompression 
flight 811 returned to honolulu after the harrowing incident on 
a scheduled flight to new zealand five other passengers were 
seriously hurt and 33 received minor injuries when the plane 
decompressed the flight carried a crew of 18 and 337 passengers 
the ntsb cited united for failing to maintain and inspect the 
door properly it said boeing and the faa failed to take timely 
corrective action after a door on a pan american boeing 747 popped 
partially open over the atlantic in 1987 
contributing to the cause of the flight 811 accident was a 
deficiency in the design of the cargo door locking mechanisms 
which made them susceptible to inservice damage and which allowed 
the door to be unlatched yet to show a properly latched and locked 
position the board said 
the latch indicator systems would be changed with an imminent 
faa order that would require detectors on the locks investigators 
said 
the ntsb issued a list of recommendations to ensure that cargo 
doors are properly latched and that passengers can be safety 
evacuated from an aircraft it also recommended that emergency 
vehicles at the honolulu airport be painted in highly visible 
colors rather than military camouflage patterns that cannot be seen 
at night 
ntsb conclusions and recommendations carry no judicial weight 
and its determination of a probable cause may not be introduced as 
evidence in court cases 
lawyer arthur wolk of philadelphia who has brought several 
cases against airlines and manufacturers for safety deficiencies 
praised the ntsb findings as the first time the board has come up 
with the right conclusion and the right cause of an accident 
it shows they have the courage to assess blame properly 
said wolk hopefully this will lead to greater faa oversight of 
the industry which is seeing steppedup production he and other 
safety advocates have criticized the faa for giving airlines too 
long to correct cargo door deficiencies and other problems 
if you dont act in an immediate fashion when you deal with 
aviation youre going to kill somebody wolk said 
united spokesman robert dowdy said the airline properly 
maintained and inspected the door of the plane used for flight 811 
although he acknowledged that a required december 1988 inspection 
was omitted because of a clerical error 
boeing had recommended that the board conclude that probable 
cause of the incident could not be determined 
in seattle boeing spokesman jack gamble noted that changes have 
been made in the doors and in inspection processes since the 
accident 
all of the necessary actions have been taken to ensure 
integrity of that doors operation in flight he said 
