<TEXT>
a strong easter holiday weekend could boost 
greyhound lines inc to the financial breakeven point as it 
attempts to rebuild from a lengthy bus drivers strike says 
president frank schmieder 
the fiveday easter travel period ending monday is one of the 
five busiest times of the year for greyhound 
schmieder said in an interview this week that the company 
projects revenue in the next few days will be between 70 percent 
and 73 percent of revenue at the same time last year 
seventythree percent of revenue is cash break even and when 
we do that we figure weve turned the corner said schmieder 
jeffrey nelson a spokesman for the amalgamated council of 
greyhound local unions called greyhounds latest claims 
preposterous 
theyve been claiming the turned corners for the last six 
weeks said nelson 
the companys 6300 drivers and about 3000 of its office and 
maintenance workers walked out march 2 in an argument over wages 
and job security greyhound has been operating a reduced schedule 
since using permanent replacements and drivers willing to cross 
picket lines 
negotiations have been stalled since last month the company has 
refused to bargain until seven days have passed without major 
violence against its buses which have been hit by gunfire and 
suffered other attacks 
the company also filed a 30 million federal lawsuit earlier 
this week charging the union was behind the violence the union 
claims the company is using the violence as an excuse to avoid 
negotiations 
greyhound has increased service in stages with the latest 
addition scheduled for thursday when the company plans to add 
almost 100000 miles putting it at 458595 miles or 718 percent 
of prestrike levels 
schmieder said on march 28 that the strike was essentially 
over in much of the country as the company continued expanding 
to cover more of its prestrike routes 
union officials claim greyhound actually is operating only about 
20 percent of its prestrike routes 
through easter greyhound is offering free tickets if its buses 
are late in the busy northeast where strike service has been 
hardest hit 
schmieder said the promotion has been effective with about 800 
passengers or 14 percent of the total getting free tickets in 
the first five days of the offer business in the region has risen 
to about 12000 passengers a day from around 8000 
passenger volumes nationwide totaled more than more than 56 
percent of the volume for the same day last year according to 
company figures 
p anthony lannie greyhounds executive vice president said 
the company should be serving 95 percent of its routes by summer 
although cutbacks are possible when the slower fall season arrives 
lannie said greyhound will have 3200 drivers by may 1 but will 
need at least 1000 more to meet summer demand 
while passenger traffic may be growing the company is missing 
out on money from its small package express business which 
accounted for about 92 million of greyhounds 104 billion in 
revenue last year 
schmieder said the package business is at about 45 percent of 
yearearlier levels although he expects the increased service to 
raise that to 50 percent 
greyhounds charter operation which last year brought in 90 
million has been almost nonexistent during the strike as the 
company has used drivers for its mainline operations 
greyhound lines was created three years ago in a debtfinanced 
buyout of the bus operations of greyhound corp later that year 
greyhound lines also bought the dallasbased operator of the 
largest trailways bus system 
despite its reduced cash flow greyhound has continued to pay 
its bills schmieder says the next interest payment is due may 15 
and if we had to make the payment today we could do it 
