<TEXT>
the federal government joined a former 
northrop corp employee wednesday in suing the defense contractor 
for allegedly overbilling the navy by millions of dollars on parts 
for the fa18 fighterbomber 
northrop was accused of developing in 1985 an improved cheaper 
way of producing composite fuselage parts for the plane without 
passing on the savings to the navy or telling the pentagon about 
the improvement 
the civil suit one of several accusing northrop of overbilling 
or improper testing was filed by former employee eldon janssen 
under a federal act that allows people to sue government suppliers 
for alleged fraud 
details of the action were unsealed after the government 
intervened wednesday 
the government has not yet determined the exact amount of the 
damages the justice department said in a statement estimates 
however range into the millions of dollars 
northrop spokesman tony cantafio declined to comment because 
officials had not seen the lawsuit 
the lawsuit is one in a series of legal actions against northrop 
last month the justice department sued northrop for more than 
5 million in civil damages after the company pleaded guilty in a 
criminal case to lying about performing all required tests on parts 
for the marine corps av8b harrier jet 
the company agreed to pay a 17 million fine in a criminal case 
concerning the harrier 
northrop also has been accused of making political payoffs to 
south koreans and overcharging the air force by 20 billion on the 
b2 stealth bomber 
the b2 suit like the action over the fa18 was a socalled 
whistle blower case filed by former employees 
